\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sentence Embedding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several different terms have been used to decribe the notion of a sentence
 embedding.
 It is called a phrase embedding in the work of Sorcher et Al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SocherEtAl2013:CVG,SocherEtAl2011:PoolRAE,Socher2011ParsingPhrases,socher2010PhraseEmbedding,SocherEtAl2011:RAE"

\end_inset

, and is one form of what is called a paragraph or document embedding in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "le2014distributed"

\end_inset

.
 Semantically, a sentence is the expression of a single idea.
 Thus embedding sentences into vector spaces is the same as embedding ideas
 into vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Semantic Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sentences are said to be semantically equivalent if they each imply the
 other -- the relationship is that of bidirectional entailment.
 If we consider two sentences A and B.
 A is equivalent to B if A being true implies that B also must be true,
 and if B is true then A also must be true.
 This definition is closely related to that for logical equivalence.
 Different equivalent sentences are said to be paraphrases of each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paraphrases from the Microsoft Research Paraphrase Corpus (MSRPC) were
 judged by the human raters to have the same high-level meaning, and to
 show 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mostly bidirectional entailment
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "msrParapharaCorpus"

\end_inset

.
 That is to say, that while each sentence may contain information which
 is not implied by the other, the core meaning of the sentences is entailed
 by both.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "msrParapharaCorpus"

\end_inset

 provides the examples of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Sentence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A: Charles O.
 Prince, 53, was named as Mr.
 Weill’s successor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Sentence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

B: Mr.
 Weill’s longtime confidant, Charles O.
 Prince, 53, was named as his successor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While additional information is present in Sentence B, still each sentence
 implies most of the meaning of the other.
 Thus while not semantically equivalent, they are considered semantically
 close.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that that semantic similarity is often defined differently
 for words.
 While semantic similarity for sentences is defined in terms of shared meaning
 and mutual entailment, semantic similarity for words can be defined in
 terms of shared properties
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "manning1999foundations"

\end_inset

.
 For example: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fall
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are antonyms, but are under the aforementioned definition for word semantic
 similarity are very similar: they both describe an vertical change in (potentia
lly metaphorical) position.
 However, the sentences 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The share price is predicted to rise.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The share price is predicted to fall.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are not semantically similar sentences, as they do not imply each other
 - in-fact each implies that the other is false.
 This sentence definition of semantic equivalence can be seen to be essential
 in applications such as machine translation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Substitution Based Evaluation Corpus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method proposed here to evaluate the semantic localization requires
 the construction of a corpus which contains semantically close and semantically
 distant sentences.
 To allow discrimination between embeddings which capture structure (syntax)
 or word content, and those which capture meaning, the semantically distinct
 sentences should have the same structure and word content except for the
 variations evaluated.
 Thus a method is required to change the meaning of sentences, without changing
 anything else.
 To change meaning at least one word must be changed.
 As the key action or statement of a sentence clause is given by its verb
