\begin_layout Standard
To contrast this, and see the effect of simply changing words, but not structure
 or meaning, a second method is used.
 For this evaluation, nouns are replaced with their synonyms.
 Thus the structure and meaning are preserved, and only the word content
 is changed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Validity of Substitutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the basic tests for determining the part of speech a word of unknown
 lexical category is to substitute a word of known category i
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mihalcea2006corpus"

\end_inset

n its place, if the sentence is still correct, then the unknown word may
 have that category
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "radford2004minimalist"

\end_inset

.
 For example if a sentence contains the never seen word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

foobar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and substituting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in its place is grammatical, it can be concluded that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

foobar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is most likely also a noun.
 It has been suggested that this is the mechanism by which people learn
 the parts of speech relations.
 In general, substitutions of the same parts of speech are valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As synonyms and antonyms make up the same parts of speech as their base
 form, it is grammatically valid to substitute for the original.
 Substituting a synonym is not expected to change the meaning of the sentence,
 thus such a substitution creates a new sentence which is semantically equivalen
t.
 Indeed this has been proposed as the very definition of synonymy (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "miller1991contextualsemantics"

\end_inset

 attributes this definition to Leibniz), though there has been some debate
 over the nature and degree of this relation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "miller1991contextualsemantics"

\end_inset

.
 It has been noted in a limited study that subjects could identify whether
 an adjective or its antonym belong in blanked out section of a sentence
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "APS:2745308"

\end_inset

.
 This suggests that identical sentences up to an antonym swap in adjectives,
 may not occur in natural English
